When u got alotta many categorical vars¶

So back when we started cleaning the variables, to try to reduce the dimensionality of this data set, there are alot of incredibly unbalanced variables. This means that class occurance of the non-primary class is so low that they almost have no variance.

Conventional wisdom dictates to just removed these in order to avoid having alot of low variance predictors. However, as I was decimating the data I was begining to wonder if this is always correct.

So I decided to see where loss occurs, and by this I mean where the most loss occurs so that we can see if removing those low-var predictors is reasonable.

For most of my EDA I used this kernel: https://www.kaggle.com/sharmasanthosh/allstate-claims-severity/exploratory-study-on-ml-algorithms

Of which, I primarily looked at the histograms of the categorical variables to see which were unbalanced

Below I am going to create a categorical variable based upon which quantile of loss the observation falls into

In [5]:
#create a categorical variable based on quantile of loss (severity)
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

le = LabelEncoder()
quant = le.fit_transform(pd.cut(dt.loss,4))
print(le.classes_)

dt['quant'] = quant

#make a list of vars to remove
conts = [i for i in dt.columns if "cont" in i]
conts.append('loss')
conts.append('quant')

quant = dt.quant

['(-120.342, 30253.565]' '(30253.565, 60506.46]' '(60506.46, 90759.355]'
 '(90759.355, 121012.25]']

So you can see that the upper bins are big and no where close to the mean. This is saying that there are gonna be outliers and my hunch is that all of those unbalanced variabels are going to contain informatuon about outliers with them occuring in one of those non-primary classes.

So what is my obsession with this tail u ask? Well the idea is that standard methods of regression are great for describing what the data looks like 'on average' but as we have see the average is not a good descriptor for this data. So I am attempting to help our algorithm inimize loss by figuring out which categorical variables are indicative of a higher quantile loss and making sure I do not reuse them.

One other method for this I would ty would be to train a 4 classed classifier to predict what bin the response will fall in because that is easier, and if that classification has small amounts of error, predict it's output and then include that variable in the regression method that you are using.

That wasn't the best explanation, but the gist is:

Outliers ain't gonna be outliers in loss and nothing else
In [6]:
#calculate the avg. quantile by class of var
sev = []
for i in dt.drop(conts, axis=1).columns:
    if dt[i][dt[i] > 0].sum() > 10:
        sev.append((i,np.sum(dt[i]*quant)/(dt[i][dt[i] > 0].sum())))
In [7]:
#create a dataframe of the the score
score = pd.DataFrame(sev)
score.columns = ['name', 'val']
score.index = score.name

#get the top 100 vars for quantile metric
smscore = score.sort_values('val', ascending=False).iloc[0:100,]
In [8]:
#grab some results vars
mns = []
sds = []
ns = []
total = []
for name in smscore.index:
    mns.append(dt[dt[name] > 0].loss.mean())
    sds.append(dt[dt[name] > 0].loss.std())
    ns.append(len(dt[dt[name] > 0]))
    total.append(dt[dt[name] > 0].loss.sum())
    
smscore['avg_loss'] = mns
smscore['std_loss'] = sds
smscore['ocs'] = ns
smscore['sum_loss'] = total

So you can see that the average is really high for the top 30 or so, but not too many of those have very many samples. Also alot of these categories come from variables that have a lot of categories.

In [12]:
#total value of loss occured in data
total_loss = dt.loss.sum()
high_quant_loss = smscore.sum_loss.sum()

print('Total Loss: \t %s \nTop 100 Loss:\t %s' % (total_loss, high_quant_loss))

Total Loss: 	 571985358.29 
Top 100 Loss:	 1191801361.51

So alot of loss is double counted here and I think that really enforces my point. We took the 100 categories that have the highest quantile score and were able to produce double the loss than was availible in this data. Therefore, as I said previously outliers in loss find themselves into rare categories in other variables.

I would conclude that it would be a bad idea to remove any of the varables that accouted for this much loss.

# Generate a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

# Set up the matplotlib figure
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))

# Generate a custom diverging colormap
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap=True)

# Draw the heatmap with the mask and correct aspect ratio
